stimulus:
You are participating in an experiment at the Vision Lab of the Department of Cognitive Science, Central European University. One of our main questions is what kind of representations we can create about our visual environment and how these representations influence our behavior. At our lab we use multiple methods, for example behavioral experiments and computational models. In this experiment you will observe scenes consisting of abstract shapes and answer simple questions about them.

At the beginning and throughout the experiment you will receive precise information about what to do. The experiment takes about 25 minutes in total.

The test is voluntary, and you can withdraw your participation at any time. We treat your personal information confidentially.
Only those people who work on this research project have access to your data. We will work with group level statistics. We will only report the results of the group in scientific publications and conferences. This research was approved by the Hungarian Psychological Research Ethics Committee.

If you have any further questions about the study, you can contact the experimenter, Beata Tunde Szabo, PhD Student. Contact: 1051 Nador u. 11. E-mail: szabo_beata-tunde@phd.ceu.edu

By pressing the button below you indicate that you read this information, found it sufficent, and you consent to participate in the experiment.

This is your practice session. You will see a checkerboard with random simple shapes appearing in different positions in the checkerboard. Your task is simply to observe the patterns so that you would be able to answer some questions about the sequence after the practice session. The session will last for about 15 minutes. Please, pay attention to EACH display!

Occasionally, there will be an attention check asking you to press the spacebar.

Your practice session is now over.

The test session will start in 2 minutes.

You can use these two minutes to relaxe your eyes.

This is your test session. You will see 36 trials. In each trial two pairs of shapes will appear with one second of pause between them. Your task is to decide which of the two pairs looks more familiar based on the practice session you have just seen. After the second shape-pair a dialog window will appear asking whether the first or the second pair was more familiar. Using the keyboard you should press 1 or 2.
Pressing 1 means that the first shape-pair is more familiar.
Pressing 2 means that the second shape-pair is more familiar.
No other inputs are accepted.
It is important that you pay attention to each trial and that you reply to each trial to the best of your knowledge. Always reply either 1 or 2, even if you are unsure.

responses:
{"Q0":"I think it can be two different things; about subconsciously recognising a pattern and seeing if that influences the answers. The other one could be seeing if, after a long time showing different images, if a person would start searching for patterns to follow. In my case I did notice all of the patterns the figures were following conciously:
- The star would always go above the sunrise shape.
- The black arrow would always be diagonally to the left-down side of the right-left arrow touching.
- The middle bar with the big circle would always be to the left of the vertical bar with a circle on each side.
- The flag would go above the shape with a wall to its left.
- The tombstone shape would go to the left of the kind of electrical shape.
- The Z would go diagonally up-left to the last, unmentioned shape."}

{"Q0":"Yes I did. I just typed them in the last textbox.
First of, every shape had a pair to them. They'd follow some rules:
- The position of each shape respectively to their pair would always remain unchanged.
- The position of the pair as a whole would be placed in different boxes of the grid.
- There would always be three empty boxes.
Now, the pairs of each shape and their position are:
- The star would go directly above the sunrise shape.
- The arrow pointing down would go in the box to the left-down of the horizontal arrows facing each-other.
- The diagonal bar with the circle in the middle would go directly to the left of the vertical bar with a circle on top and bottom.
- The tombstone shape would go to the left of the electrical shape? I don't know how to describe that one.
- The flag shape would go directly above the one shape with the wall facing to the left side.
- The Z shape would go up and left to the final, unmentioned shape."}

{"Q0":"I've participated in pattern recognision experiments, but they would give context to them from before so unlike here, I was already looking for patterns in them instead of figuring out what was happening."}
